<h1><img src="/pub/Graphics/Icons/earth4_icon.gif" ALT="">
<a name="top">EFF &quot;Information Infrastructure (Global/National)&quot; Archive</a></h1>

<H5>http://www.eff.org/pub/GII_NII/
</H5>



<h6>Last Updated Wed Nov 06 11:26:20 PDT 1996</h6><br>
<TABLE BORDER=4 CELLPADDING=4 CELLSPACING=4>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
<TD><A HREF="#files">Files</A></TD><h6></h6>
<TD><A HREF="#dirs">Subdirectories</A></TD><h6></h6>
<TD><A HREF="#onsite">On-Site Links</A></TD><h6></h6>
<TD><A HREF="#offsite">Off-Site Links</A></TD>
</TR></TABLE>


<P></CENTER><BR><HR>
<BR><h2><A NAME="files">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/doc1_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40 ALT=""></A>
Files in this Archive</h2>

<DL>
<DT><a href="cable_net_resources.faq"><B>cable_net_resources.faq</B></a>
<DD>Frequently Asked questions about Cable TV 
    Resources on the Net, compiled by Multichannel News. Updated 9/94
<DT><a href="cix_isp_telecom_policy_95.paper"><B>cix_isp_telecom_policy_95.paper</B></a>
<DD>Commercial Internet eXchange (CIX) 
    white paper on Internet Service Provider (ISP) telecommunications policy
    framework issues. March 1995.
<DT><a href="coalition_public_nii.letter"><B>coalition_public_nii.letter</B></a>
<DD>letter to Sens. Hollings (D-SC) and Inouye 
    (D-HI), with accompanying press release, asking them to reserve capacity 
    on the NII for noncommercial educational and informational services 
    (5/12/93)
<DT><a href="corp_public_cybercast.proposal"><B>corp_public_cybercast.proposal</B></a>
<DD>April 1993 article &quot; TOWARD THE 
    FORMATION OF A CORPORATION FOR PUBLIC CYBERCASTING&quot; by T.M Grundner
    which outlines the need, structure, and rationale for a &quot;Corporation
    for Public Cybercasting&quot; -- an organization which would do for
    public access information age services what the Corporation for
    Public Broadcasting did for public radio and tv.
<DT><a href="darkfiber.article"><B>darkfiber.article</B></a>
<DD>Wired interview with George Gilder (Wired 1.4)
<DT><a href="dc_bogeymen_gilder.article"><B>dc_bogeymen_gilder.article</B></a>
<DD>Series of articles by George Gilder about 
    the &quot;monsters,&quot; as perceived by the government, in the communication and 
    information industries
<DT><a href="democracy_and_network_interconnectivity.paper"><B>democracy_and_network_interconnectivity.paper</B></a>
<DD>
<DT><a href="democracy_online.article"><B>democracy_online.article</B></a>
<DD>Evan Schwartz's Wired 2.01 article discussing
    the concept of an Electronic Town Hall
<DT><a href="econ_dereg_effects_wefa.paper"><B>econ_dereg_effects_wefa.paper</B></a>
<DD>WEFA paper on the effects of 
    telecommunications deregualation (7/93)
<DT><a href="ftp_rboc_nii.announce"><B>ftp_rboc_nii.announce</B></a>
<DD>Announcement of an ftp server maintained by the 
    Baby Bells
<DT><a href="gii_concerns_farber_021895_eff.speech"><B>gii_concerns_farber_021895_eff.speech</B></a>
<DD>&quot;Living in the Global Information 
    Infrastructure&quot; -- a sppech by David Farber, 2/18/95
<DT><a href="gii_expression_letter.eff"><B>gii_expression_letter.eff</B></a>
<DD>A letter from EFF and many other non-profits 
    to Vice President Al Gore regarding GII priorities and freedom of 
    expression. (2/16/95)
<DT><a href="havenots_forum_052494.transcript"><B>havenots_forum_052494.transcript</B></a>
<DD>Unofficial transcript from a National 
    Press Foundation Forum (5/24/94) &quot;Is There a Place for Have-Nots in 
    Cyberspace?&quot;
<DT><a href="highway_to_where_moore.article"><B>highway_to_where_moore.article</B></a>
<DD>1995 article by Dr. Gale Moore, &quot;Highway 
    to Where? The Real Questions Are Social Not Technical&quot;, outlining
    social implications of telepresence and other communications technologies.
<DT><a href="hiways_of_mind.article"><B>hiways_of_mind.article</B></a>
<DD>Detailed article by Roget Karraker, 
    originally published in Whole Earth Review Spring 1991 (issue #70), on 
    the history of the internet and possibilities of future development and 
    organization
<DT><a href="ii.sourcebook"><B>ii.sourcebook</B></a>
<DD>Table of contents and information about the Information 
    Infrastructure Sourcebook, published by Harvard's Kennedy School of 
    Government (note dated 12/17/93)
<DT><a href="iitf_principles_comments.eff"><B>iitf_principles_comments.eff</B></a>
<DD>EFF comments on the IITF's &quot;Principles for 
    Providing and Using Personal Information&quot;
<DT><a href="info_railroad_usenix_barlow_eff.speech"><B>info_railroad_usenix_barlow_eff.speech</B></a>
<DD>John Perry Barlow's 1/17/94 
    speech to the winter 1993 USENIX Conference about the internet, the 
    &quot;highway&quot; metaphor (which he considers inappropriate), and the future
    of the internet, as it is viewed by the government, industry, and himself
<DT><a href="infobahn_jackboots_barlow_eff.article"><B>infobahn_jackboots_barlow_eff.article</B></a>
<DD>John Perry Barlow's 2/9/94 
    article in Wired 2.04 abou the Clipper chip, with a comprehensive 
    background on the controversy, and some excellent arguments against the 
    Clipper chip
<DT><a href="jefferson_ascendant_post_eff.article"><B>jefferson_ascendant_post_eff.article</B></a>
<DD>&quot;Jefferson Ascendant&quot; article by
    EFF Policy Fellow David Post, 1995. A look at the warring Jeffersonian
    &amp; Hamiltonian political philosophies behind todays battle between civil
    libertarians and authoritarian regulators over the fate of the Internet.
<DT><a href="labor_dereg_effects.paper"><B>labor_dereg_effects.paper</B></a>
<DD>paper from the Economic Policy Institute 
    entitled &quot;Good Jobs at Good Wages: the Characteristics of Jobs Created by 
    Lifting Line-of-Business-Restrictions in Telecommunications for Baby 
    Bells.&quot; The authors contend that lifting such restrictions would create 
    many new jobs with good benefits
<DT><a href="latino_ii_rivera.brief"><B>latino_ii_rivera.brief</B></a>
<DD>policy brief, &quot;Latinos and the Information 
    Superhighway,&quot; from the Tomas Rivera Center (9/94)
<DT><a href="life_after_tv_gilder.article"><B>life_after_tv_gilder.article</B></a>
<DD>George Gilder article &quot;Life After 
    Television,&quot; in which he discusses the race between computer companies 
    and cable television companies to provide access to the &quot;information 
    superhighway,&quot; and whhy he thinks that computer companies are far better 
    prepared to do so
<DT><a href="net_subsidy_schickele.paper"><B>net_subsidy_schickele.paper</B></a>
<DD>paper by Sandra Schickele in which she 
    argues that the free market will not provide an adequate supply of net 
    services without government subsidies
<DT><a href="new_delhi.declaration"><B>new_delhi.declaration</B></a>
<DD>Declaration of principles of the participants of 
    the Symposium on New Technologies and the Democratisation of 
    Audiovisual Communication, which took place in New Delhi from 2/9/94 to 
    2/12/94
<DT><a href="nii_articles.note"><B>nii_articles.note</B></a>
<DD>Data from USA Today: the number of articles, by 
    month, about the &quot;information highway&quot; in 150 US newspapers in 1993
<DT><a href="nii_competition_telco_94.paper"><B>nii_competition_telco_94.paper</B></a>
<DD>Paper from the Council on 
    Competitiveness entitled &quot;Competition Policy: Unlocking the National 
    Information Infrastructure.&quot; Also contains a press release regarding the 
    paper
<DT><a href="nii_kapor_berman_eff_nyt.article"><B>nii_kapor_berman_eff_nyt.article</B></a>
<DD>Article from the New York TImes 
    (11/24/93) by Mitchell Kapor and Jerry Berman, advocating the &quot;open 
    platform,&quot; allowing every person access to the &quot;information superhighway&quot; 
    as both a consumer and a potential producer
<DT><a href="nii_kapor_eff_wired.article"><B>nii_kapor_eff_wired.article</B></a>
<DD>Wired 1.3 article by Mitchell Kapor 
    entitled &quot;Where is the Digital Highway Really Heading?&quot; Kapor details 
    steps already taken toward implementing the National Information 
    Infrastructure, and the role the government should play in developing the 
    rest of the NII
<DT><a href="pac_94_contributions.list"><B>pac_94_contributions.list</B></a>
<DD>1994 CyberWire Dispatch about communications 
    industry PAC donations to senators and representatives
<DT><a href="pac_contributions.article"><B>pac_contributions.article</B></a>
<DD>1994 Cyberwire Dispatch by Brock Meeks about 
    communications PAC donations leading up to the 1994 congressional 
    election
<DT><a href="pub-int_summit_94.summary"><B>pub-int_summit_94.summary</B></a>
<DD>Summary of the proceedings of the NII Public 
    Interest Summit (3/29/94), posted to the net by an audience member as 
    the summit progressed
<DT><a href="pub-int_summit_94_summary.eff"><B>pub-int_summit_94_summary.eff</B></a>
<DD>EFF Summary of the proceedings of the NII 
    Public Interest Summit (3/29/94). For the most part, the same 
    information as in pub-int_summit_94.summary but more formal
<DT><a href="rboc_revenue.chart"><B>rboc_revenue.chart</B></a>
<DD>graph from Telecommunications Magazine showing the 
    relative size of the RBOCs
<DT><a href="rickard_nii.article"><B>rickard_nii.article</B></a>
<DD>exceprt from a Boardwatch Magazine editorial by 
    Jack Rickard in which he rails against most government involvement in the 
    development of the NII, health care, and especially in the field of 
    encryption
<DT><a href="tbs_v_fcc_must-carry.decision"><B>tbs_v_fcc_must-carry.decision</B></a>
<DD>Supreme Court decision in the Turner 
    Broadcasting System, Inc., et al., v. FCC 
<DT><a href="technopolicy_eur.article"><B>technopolicy_eur.article</B></a>
<DD>Article by John Browning from Wired 1.2 in 
    which he discusses European (specifically French, English, and German) 
    industrial and technological subsidies, and the mixed results that they 
    have achieved, and the lessons to be learned from European mistakes that 
    should be applied to American technological policy
<DT><a href="telecom_pubs.list"><B>telecom_pubs.list</B></a>
<DD>list of telecommunications publications and how to 
    reach them
<DT><a href="tv_interactive.article"><B>tv_interactive.article</B></a>
<DD>Article by Jules Marshall from Wired 1.5 about 
    an interactive television experiment based in Germany, the sucess of its 
    first attempt at interactive TV, and the people designing the experiment
<DT><a href="uswest_contact.list"><B>uswest_contact.list</B></a>
<DD>contact list of telecommunications corporations in 
    the western US
<DT><a href="video_dialtone_berman_eff_fcc_020392.testimony"><B>video_dialtone_berman_eff_fcc_020392.testimony</B></a>
<DD>Jerry Berman's testimony 
    before the FCC regarding telephone company/cable television 
    cross-ownershiip rules. Berman stresses the importance of two-way 
    information flow, both to the home and from the home, the importance of 
    allowing technological change to evolve, rather than implementing a rigid 
    network that may be unable to accomodate future innovations, and the 
    importance of ensuring equitable access to the NII.
<DT><a href="video_dialtone_eff.article"><B>video_dialtone_eff.article</B></a>
<DD>position paper by Daniel Weitzner explaining 
    that video dialtone will use market forces to bring net access to more 
    people
<DT><a href="virtual_frontier_barlow_eff.article"><B>virtual_frontier_barlow_eff.article</B></a>
<DD>&quot;Jack In, Young Pioneer,&quot; by John 
    Perry Barlow, The Inside Passage, 8/11/94. A brief, wonderfully amusing 
    and insightful article comparing cyberspace the the American West of days 
    past, but optimistically suggesting that the electronic frontier will 
    never be civilized.
<DT><a href="wolf_iway_robber_barons.article"><B>wolf_iway_robber_barons.article</B></a>
<DD>Article by Joshua Wolf Shenk, 
    originally published in The Washington Monthly, comparing cable and 
    communications giants of today to the railway robber barons of the 
    nineteenth century
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
<H2><A NAME="dirs">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/filefolder_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40
ALT=""></A> Subdirectories in This Archive</H2>

<DL>
<DT><A HREF=".."><B>Up to the Parent Directory</B><P></a>
<DT><a href="Censorship/"><B>Censorship/</B></A>
<DD>link to directory containing information on Internet, BBS and 
    GII/NII free expression and censorship issues
<DT><a href="Comm_Decency_Act/"><B>Comm_Decency_Act/</B></A>
<DD>link to directory containing information on the 
    Exon/Gorton &quot;Communications Decency&quot; legislation of 1994-95.
<DT><a href="Commerce_online/"><B>Commerce_online/</B></A>
<DD>directory of information on electronic commerce, online
    advertising, digital transactions, and related issues.
<DT><a href="Foreign_and_local/"><B>Foreign_and_local/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info on information infrastructure issues
    at the state, local, regional, global, and non-US national levels.
<DT><a href="Govt_docs/"><B>Govt_docs/</B></A>
<DD>directory of government documents, including agency statements,
    testimony by executive branch
<DT><a href="Internet_telephony/"><B>Internet_telephony/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info on the development of, and disputes
    surrounding, &quot;voice on the Net&quot; or Internet telephony.
<DT><a href="ISDN/"><B>ISDN/</B></A>
<DD>directory of information on ISDN (Integrated Services Digital 
    Network) telecom technology &amp; policy.
<DT><a href="NREN_NSFNET_NPN/"><B>NREN_NSFNET_NPN/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info on NSFNet and the NREN (National 
    Research &amp; Education Network) and NPN (National Public Network) plan 
    (a sort of prototype &quot;data superhighway&quot; idea) from the late 80s and
    early 90s. Primarily of historical interest.
<DT><a href="Old/"><B>Old/</B></A>
<DD>directory of outdated, but still historically interesting, material
    on EFF's Open Platform initiative, and GII/NII issues in general. 
<DT><a href="Privacy/"><B>Privacy/</B></A>
<DD>link to directory of NII, GII, email, Internet/Usenet and BBS
    privacy issues &amp; information.
<DT><a href="Regional_rural_edu/"><B>Regional_rural_edu/</B></A>
<DD>(a.k.a. Academic_edu/, Tele-education/) directory of 
    files about academic, educational, regional, and rural networking.
<DT><a href="Telecommuting_telework/"><B>Telecommuting_telework/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info telecommunting, telework, 
    working at home via networking, and the social, economic, technical 
    and political issues related to this shift in employment.
<DT><a href="Telemedicine/"><B>Telemedicine/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info on distance medicine, medical networking.
<DT><a href="Wireless_cellular_radio/"><B>Wireless_cellular_radio/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info on networking and 
    telecommunications via cellular technology, packet radio, satellite, 
    and other wireless techniques; concentrates on political, economic and 
    social, rather than technical, issues.
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
