<H2><IMG SRC="mcc_red_icon.gif" ALT="" BORDER=0 WIDTH=79 HEIGHT=79">M[a]cCandlish/M[a]cCandless
Tartan</H2>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#INTRO">Intro</A>
<LI><A HREF="#IMAGES">Images</A>
<LI><A HREF="#TC">Thread Count Chart</A>
<LI><A HREF="#FAQ">Frequently Asked Questions (&amp; Answers)</A>
<LI><A HREF="../whatsnew.html">What's New?</A>
</UL>

<BR><HR><BR>

<H3><A NAME="INTRO">Intro</A></H3>
The M[a]cCandlish/M[a]cCandless tartan was devised by Stanton McCandlish, in
1992.
<P>

The tartan is loosely based on the Black Watch family of tartans, with their
"tramtrack" patterns (the thin black lines), but with unusual proportioning. 
The tartan is also almost unique in having muliple tones of the same 
basic color (the only other example I can recall is Anderson, which has 
two blues, and a single regional tartan, the name of which I forget).  
The result is a pleasing subtlety and understatedness. Like most tartans, 
this is a symetric tartan - the pattern is repeated in mirror image in 
all four directions (a handful of tartans are repeated without 
"mirroring")<P>


<BR><HR><BR>

