<P>
<H4>Color Key</H4>
<UL> 
<LI>Ye = yellow
<LI>Bk = black
<LI>Wh = white
<LI>Gn = green (standard dark green)
<LI>LG = light green (as used in a few other tartans)
<LI>Rd = red (standard vibrant red)
<LI>Cr = crimson (dark red, as used in a few other tartans)
<LI>Az = azure (light blue as in Anderson tartan & a few others)
<LI>GL = light grey (as used in a few other tartans)
<LI>GD = dark grey (standard grey as found in many tartans)
</UL>
<P><HR><BR>

<H3><A NAME="FAQ">Frequently Asked Questions (&amp; Answers)</A></H3>

Q) How can you just invent a tartan? Isn't that inauthentic?
<BR>
A) Certainly not.  Clan tartans did not exist until the 1700s
(with tartans being adopted by chiefs as "official" clan tartans only 
since the 1820s or later in almost all cases, most well into the 20th 
Century. Some clan chieftainships date to this period as well, and some 
"clans" are not even clans in the Highland sense, just family 
associations). A single exception to the 1700s dating is known from 
1618. Before the tartan, heraldic devices, what plant one wore in the 
cockade of one's hat, and other identifying marks were used to tell one 
clan from another. 

<P>Many clan tartans were invented 
literally out of whole cloth by English tailors, during the mid-to-late 
1800s, and many popular and accepted tartans date to the 20th Century, as do 
most of the regional or district tartans.  The family & clan tartans 
were created in the "Celtic 
Twighlight" period of Walter Scott and Robert Burns, William Butler 
Yeats and Lady Augusta Gregory - a romantic time that had more patience 
for spirit and enthusiasm than for historical accuracy.  But, though 
(contrary 
to popular belief) they do not represent ancient clan traditions, tartans
were rapidly adopted by clans and families, regardless of the 
particular tartan's origin, and today certainly represent gradually 
renewed interest in the part of the Scots in their own unique cultural 
identity. Tartan has indeed become something of a symbol for 
"Scottishness". <P>

And tartans, in the sense of general checkered or striped patterns of 
woolen (and on the Continent, probably flaxen) cloth, as well as kilts in 
one form or another, appear to date back at least as far as the 10th 
century, possibly even earlier: Romans refered to continental Celts 
around the time of Christ as wearing "striped" or "checkered" cloth, and 
the kilt itself is (according to one 
popular theory) the Celts' adaptation of the Roman military tunic.
The Celts of the British Isles had ample opportunity to observe this
fashion/uniform, during the Roman occupation of much of Britain. Arthurian
scholars frequently suggest that the upper eschelons of Celtic culture
adopted many "Romanisms" after the Romans left and the Dark Ages descended,
bringing waves of invaders and a renewed desire & need for inter-tribal
leadership among the Celts.  It seems likely that such a tradition as the 
wearing of Romanesque clothing would have transferred from the native 
Cumbrian and Pictish chieftains to the Scoti successors after the 
Dalriadic invasions that turned Pictland into present day Scotland - 
especially if recent theories placing the seat of Arthurian power in 
Stirlingshire, Scotland, are correct.<P>

So, there is actual history and tradition behind Highland dress, even if 
it is mingled with a bit of more recent creative energy (and one supposes 
that this admixture couldn't really be any other way - if the wearers of 
a form of clothing, in the modern world, do not use their imaginations, 
adapt to modern needs, and change the fashions and colors and such just 
to keep things interesting, their clothing becomes a rigidly defined but 
comical costume.  May that never happen to the kilt!)
<P>
So, in closing on this question, let me just say this:
There is nothing unusual or "bad" about new tartans, especially for names 
that previously didn't have one.  Remember: Even the oldest clan tartans 
aren't very old, and came about in exactly the same way - someone came up 
with a pattern, or found one, and promulgated it as the family tartan.  Even 
the English royal family have their own tartan, after all.  And how 
further away from the Highlander can you get? :-)<P><BR>

Q) What bodies recognize the M[a]cCandlish/M[a]cCandless tartan?
<BR>
A)It is "registered" with the Tartan Educational &amp; Cultural 
Association (and appears in TECA's TartanArt database/graphics 
generator). It is not yet registered with the Lord Lyon (this may only be 
possible with clan tartans, for currently existing clans with titled 
chiefs - I am not certain yet), nor with the Scottish Tartans Society (in 
danger of becoming defunct). Registration with TECA also automatically 
entails having one's tartan recorded by the new Scottish Tartan Authority,
as the two organizations have merged. In any case, the point of listing 
the tartan with these organizations is simply to make it easier for more 
people to know about it, and to keep it from becoming lost, or co-opted 
by tartan mills to represent a more common name (e.g. so they can sell 
more tartan cloth).  There really aren't any legal issues at stake here.
<P><BR>
Q) Is this tartan copyrighted? Why?
<BR>
A) Yes, it is (though the copyright is not registered. I don't see any 
particular reason to register the copyright, as the extra legal protection 
afforded by doing so doesn't appear to be necessary here).
<P>
The purpose of the copyright is very straightforward: To prevent the
usurpation of the design by a few tartan woolen mills who like the 
pattern but want to sell it to a more numerous family and ergo make more 
money. Use of the tartan by Cuindlis-descended folks, or honest merchants for
that matter, is in no way restricted. Incidentally, I have never heard of
a demonstrated case of woolen mills "stealing" tartans, just rumors that 
it has happened. As such, I do not besmirch their reputation, I am simply
taking precautions against the unlikely-but-theoretically-possible.<P>

Again, use of this tartan as a [M[a]c]Candlish (or any other 
Cuindlis-variant) family tartan, for whatever end purpose, is <b>not</b> 
under any restriction.  You are free to wear and display the tartan, sell 
items made with it, etc.  You do not have to seek permission to do this, 
for either personal or commercial reasons.  The sole restriction is that it 
may not be sold or otherwise used as another, non-related, family or 
regional tartan (i.e. it's fine if you make blankets with the tartan and 
sell them as McCanliss tartan blankents, but not as MacElfish or
North Uist tartan blankets. If you just like the pattern and use it and 
don't name it anything at all, that's fine too.)

<P>Legal eagles may want to note that both the *design* and the *thread 
count* are copyright protected works. No particular piece of cloth is 
claimed as copyright protected, as copyright law in most places, including 
the US, does not apply to actual textiles, the way it applies, for 
example, to a specific copy of a book, as well as the non-physical 
information it contains, or to a recording of a song as well as the score 
and the lyrics. That is, I am protecting the intellectual property, not 
any physical property, as the law doesn't cover textile physical property.

<P>If you want a legalese copyright license, for whatever reason, there's 
one available <A HREF="copyright.txt">here</A>.  I don't care for 
legalese myself, but... Having had to deal with distribution restrictions 
in other contexts, I know no matter how many times I say you don't 
have to ask for permission, someone will do it anyway.
<P><BR>
Q) Why does the tartan have two shades of the same color in it?
Isn't that against the "rules"?  Did you do any research before creating 
this tartan?
<P>
A) As more and more tartans are created, there is a bewildering array of 
them, many of them so similar as to be very difficult to tell apart. The 
doubled color scheme is very distinctive, and helps set this one apart.
Additionally, the creator of the tartan found the effect pleasant, and 
less garish that many tartans.  At any rate, the tartan follows all the 
"rules" of tartan design, and uses no colors that are not already in 
well-established family tartans (this will, incidentally, help ensure 
that it can be woven by any tartan mill willing to do it, since they should 
have the colors in stock.) Several months of research went into the 
design, along with detailed correspondence with tartan experts 
(including TECA, and the late J.C. Thompson, a Scottish Tartans Authority
Fellow.) And, yes, there are other tartans with two different hues of the
same basic color.<P><BR>

Q) Are we a clan? Who's the chief?  What clans are we connected with? Isn't 
this an Irish name? What about similar names like McCandliss and McCanles?
How old is this family name?  Is there a family coat of arms? Where do I 
learn more?!<P>

A) This is a family tartan, not a clan one, as there is no (extant, anyway)
McCandless/McCandlish clan.  The family (or, rather, a particular but 
rather nebulous and hard to pinpoint Scottish branch of it) is regarded by 
some as an unofficial sept of Clan MacGregor, and has ties with the 
MacGregors, Buchanans and possibly the MacArthur Campbells, ca. late 1600s -
early 1700s (the time of Rob Roy). The name is well-attested in Scotland and
Ireland as a family name at least as early as the 1200s.  The name dates to
at least as early as the 6th Century in Ireland (as a given name), and the Mac
(or U&iacute;) Cuindlis may have been one of the original Dalriadic
families of Irish Scoti who invaded Pictland (now named Scotland after these
settlers) in the Dark Ages. The Cuindlis families are most numerous in
Galloway (Scotland), Galway (Ireland), and Ulster (N. Ireland), as
well as the US, Canada, Australia and New Zealand in modern times.
The migration pattern appears to be:<P>

Central Ireland -&gt; Scotland; later cen. Ireland to US, Canada, Australia, 
New Zealand, England<BR> 

Scotland -&gt; US, Canada, Australia, NZ, England, and N. Ireland<BR>

N. Ireland -&gt; US, Canada, Australia, NZ, England, and back to Scotland 
again<BR> 

Scotland -&gt; again to US, Canada, Australia, NZ, England<P>

The same holds true for the Colonies - US Cuindlises went to New Zealand, 
and some of the Aussie members of the "clan" went to the US, and so on.
The invention of powered travel really stirred the pot, with all family 
lines, not just ours.<P>

There was a lot of jumping back and forth across the Irish Sea. The family 
must be
regarded, one supposes, as thoroughly Scots-Irish, rather than either one 
or the other.
<P>
<A HREF="/~mech/Cuindlis/variants.html">There are over 50 variants of the 
name</A>.<P>
There is no chief or other recognized family head.  Several McCandlishes,
M'Caunlesses, Mac Candlesses, etc., were armigerous (i.e. had royally-granted
coats of arms) - at least 5 crests are known.  Please note that these are 
not "family" crests or coats of arms - such honors, despite what heraldic 
product mongers in the US will tell you, belong to specific individuals, 
and are inherited; they do not belong to entire families, though it is 
permissible under Scottish heraldry law to devise clan or family "badges" 
(sometimes incorrectly called "crests")
based on (but differenced from, with a surrounding belt and buckle) an 
individual crest.  This is usually if not exclusively done with the crest 
of the clan chief, and the present author does not know if it is 
permissible to do this with any known crest held by a member of the 
family, in the absence of a recognized chief. A matter for more research.
<P>
For more info on the family, see the rest of the <A HREF="/~mech/Cuindlis">
Cuindlis Genealogy Site</A>.
<P><BR>
Q) Where can I get cloth for a kilt in this tartan?
<BR>
A) Good question. This tartan is not yet, and may never be, available 
from major suppliers of stock tartan cloth, who mostly eschew less common (= 
less saleable) names. I do know that Celtic Craft 
Centre (San Francisco, and Glasgow) and Geoffrey (Tailor) Kiltmakers Ltd. 
(Edinburgh, Glasgow, Galashiels) can have a 
kilt-length of this tartan woven - that's how I got my kilt. The weavers 
are a company in Scotland called DC Dalgleish. They are used by both of 
the kiltmakers above, and are apparently the only weavers anywhere 
who'll do high-quality custom tartans in single kilt lengths. DCD only 
deals with "the trade", so you have to go through a retailer like CCC or 
G(T)K.<P>

CCC's prices are competitive in Scotland, and 
quite good in the US.  If you get your kilt through them 
there is no extra charge for the weaving. 
You do have to go with the more expensive and higher-quality kilt 
material, as 
DC Dalgleish won't, apparently, make the lower-quality gent's kilt cloth.  
For Scots, this is probably well and proper. For Americans in hotter 
climes, like Arizona, this may be slighly disappointing, as the heavier 
weight cloth can be rather toasty in hot weather.<P>

Despite some minor snafus (mostly to do with delays caused by third 
parties like the sporran supplier), I'm pretty satisfied with CCC. 
They are friendly, their work is great quality, and the kilts are made in 
Scotland by pros, not in the US by amateurs.  The beautiful Claire is 
a good contact person, as is Chriss. <A HREF="ccc.txt">I've prepared a 
page with some sample prices, here</A>.

<P>Geoffrey (Tailor) Kiltmakers have <A 
HREF="http://www.scotweb.co.uk/Highland/Geoffrey_Tailor/">a web 
page</A>, but it doesn't have prices on them. 
<A HREF="gtk.txt">I've posted sample prices 
here</A>. I've actually been in their shop in Glasgow.
Geoffrey's is an up-scale shop, but the quality is high, the prices 
reasonable (better than some of the Inverness shops as I recall), and they
are happy to deal in US dollars, so you don't have to hassle with the 
currency exchange. G(T)K does charge a little extra for kilts done in custom 
tartan, but I hear nothing but good about the quality of their work. 
Lorna Nicholsby (101675.1173@compuserve.com) is the person to deal with 
there.

<P>For the US, I'd go with CCC, and for Scotland, I'd go with G(T)K.  
The former recommendation is based on personal experience, the later on 
reputation. Either retailer can handle orders from either hemisphere,
so pick who you like.  I'd guess that 
G(T)K will be faster as they keep more sporrans and stuff in stock, but 
people at both companies have gone out of their way to be helpful.<P>

Be prepared to wait quite a 
while - weaving takes time - and possibly to wrestle with the weavers over 
the colors. In mine, the 
dark red came out rather grapey, and there just seemed to be a lot of 
confusion on their part.  Sending them a quality color printout of one 
of the graphics will probably help. DCD does have the red version of the 
McCandlish/McCandless tartan on file. I will attempt to correspond with 
them in person and solve the color issue. Wish me luck.

<P>
If you just want a kilt length or more of the cloth, e.g. for a wrap, for 
crafts, or for a breacan feile (a "great kilt"), DCD will supply it 
(through a retailer). <A HREF="dcd.txt">The prices I've been quoted are 
listed here</A>.

<P>
Lastly, if you think you have enough family members together to get a 
large quantity of kilt cloth, it will be cheaper to order a full bolt. 
Many weavers, besides DCD, will happily to a full bolt (I don't know 
exactly how many kilts that makes) of whatever tartan you give them a 
thread count for.  It will cost a lot up front, so take up a collection 
from family members. It'll probably be over US$1,000.

<P><HR><BR>


