<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Variants of the Cuindlis Names</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ee"
vlink="03066a" alink="ff0000">

<H3>Names that are almost certainly derived from Cuind[i]lis/Cuindleas</H3>

<H5>(?) = unknown if this really exists/existed<P>

(*) = It's likely that most bearers of this name are from Cuindlis lines, 
      but that others from different families have converged on this name.<P>

(+) = These names begin with a acute-accented "O". The female versions
      would begin with N&iacute; (that's "N" followed by an 
      acute-accented "i"), and lenition on the initial consonant. E.g.
      &Oacute; Cuindlis -> N&iacute; Chuindlis (probably. I'm not much
      of an Irish language scholar.) The clan/family (that is, plural) 
      version would be U&iacute; Cuindlis, I believe (That's "U" 
      followed by acute-accented "i"). Such Gaelic effects are/were not
      generally applied to anglicized names.<P>

(-) = These names, the original Gaelic patronymics, would be, in the feminine
      (e.g. to indicate "daughter of" rather than "son of") Nic
      (or in longer form, Nighean Mhic) rather than Mac, with lenition of
      "C" to "Ch" as noted above. Such Gaelic effects are/were not
      generally applied to anglicized names.<P></H5>


Andless<BR>
