<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cuindlis (McCandlish/McCandless/Quinlisk) GeneWeb</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ee"
vlink="03066a" alink="ff0000">

<CENTER>
<H1>The Cuindlis</H1>
<H2>(McCandlish/McCandless/Quinlisk)</H2>
<H1>GenWeb Database</H1>
A <A HREF="http://sillyg.doit.com/genweb/">GenWeb</A> Database on the 
Genealogy and History of the Cuindlis Families <P><HR><BR>
</CENTER>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#INTRO">Introductory Notes</A>
<LI><A HREF="../whatsnew.html">What's New?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#DB">The Databases</A>
<LI><A HREF="#END">Closing Comments</A>
</UL>
<BR><HR><BR>

<A NAME="INTRO"><H2>Introductory Notes</H2></A>

This is a WWW genealogy (in great detail) of several families with 
surnames derived from the old Gaelic Cuindlis (also Cuindilis or Cuindleas),
the most common variants of which are McCandlish, McCandless and Quinlisk.
Also provided (in much less detail in most cases) are various 'strays', 
culled from every record I can think of (phone books, censuses, etc.), of 
unknown relation to anyone else in the database with these surnames. 
Needless to say, may people of other surnames, married into the Cuindlis 
families, are also included.<P>

If you can provide more information on any of the people in the database, 
or have info on more Cuindlis descendants who aren't in the db at all yet, 
please send it!
<P>
<HR><BR>

<A NAME="DB"><H2>The Databases</H2></A>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="SURNAMES.html">Index of surnames in the database</A> [Has 
bugs - non-7bit-ASCII characters are not translating, etc. 
(<A HREF="../fixes.html">Most serious problems fixed</A>.)
<LI><A HREF="PERSONS.html">Index of individuals in the database - 
multi-page</A> (100 per page. Loads fast, but less convenient for searching.)
<LI><A HREF="PERSONS_1FILE.html">Index of individuals in the database - 
single-page</A> (all names on one page, loads slow, but easier to use 
your browser's text-searching (or "find") function on. 
<LI><A HREF="GENDEX.txt">Text-file index of individuals,
their birth/death dates and places, but no ancestry info.</A> Intended for
database processing (the data is pipe[|]-separated values), but could be
a handy quick-reference if you need it.
<LI><A HREF="../cuindlis_960703.ged">The GEDCOM database this HTML database
was built from</A>.  If you find a person of interest in the HTML, you are 
likely to want the GEDCOM file, as it may have some (possibly even lots - 
but no promises) more info on this person.  For some families and 
individuals, I've taken quite extensive notes, none of which get exported 
to HTML, due to limitations of the program that does this exporting.
Database date: June. 3, 1996.  NOT FOR REDISTRIBUTION! Use it yourself if 
you like, but do NOT upload this to WWW genealogy databases or otherwise
redistribute. File has missing info, errors, etc., to be corrected in
later revision.
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../cuindlis_960703.ged.gz">gzip-compressed Unix version</A>
<LI><A HREF="../cuindlis_960703.ged.sea.hqx">BinHexed 
StuffIt/SEA-compressed Mac version</A>
<LI><A HREF="../cuindlis_960703_ged.zip">ZIP-compressed DOS/Win version</A>
</UL>
WARNING: This GEDCOM is *not* perfect, use with caution. May require 
hand-editing in spots to get it to work with your geneware.

<LI><A HREF="../geo-codes.list">List of country, state, county, 
province, shire, etc. abbreviations used in this database</A> (You will 
probably need this at some point, unless you're just browsing for the 
heck of it.) This list I hope to eventually work into a draft standard.  
Comments welcome. NOT FOR REDISTRIBUTION. Check it out, but don't post it -
it's in a very rough and ugly state right now.
<LI><A HREF="SOURCES.html">Index of source documents</A>. 
Besides general & specific source info, this file provides, under one entry, 
some heraldic info, so check it out if interested in that.
</UL>
<BR><HR><BR>
<A NAME="END"><H2>Closing Comments</H2></A>
The persons indexes, toward the end, also list some records I've created 
for surnames. That is, I've created a person-like record simply for a 
surname, so that I can in one place conveniently record any info about that
Cuindlis-derived surname, e.g. when it first appeared, where, etc. These
are not individuals, though the GEDCOM -&gt; HTML translator treats them 
as such, and therefore creates empty pedigree charts for them. This is 
just kind of an artifact of the HTML translation. <B>You won't find any real
info here, other than tentative dates of first appearance.</B> The real 
notes are in the GEDCOM files, also available above. The HTML translator
doesn't export this information. Sorry.<HR>

COMING IN THE FUTURE: Lots of new data, including several-100K of 
McCandless-Critchlow and related family history.  Bug fixes, as noted 
above, maps, links to good geneware, etc.  PLEASE REPORT BUGS AND TYPOS! If 
you don't, how are they to be fixed?
<HR>

 This db is in public beta test right now, and was built with an 
unregistered version of Eugene W. Stark's <B>GED2HTML</B>, a program (for 
Unix and DOS/Windows, recently ported to Mac by someone else) that processes 
GEDCOM genealogical databases into HTML files.  When I'm sure all works 
well, I will certainly register the program.  My GEDCOM database was 
created with (a registered copy of) Diana &amp; David Eppstein's 
<A HREF="http://www.ics.uci.edu/~eppstein/gene">Gene</A>, a genealogy program for the Mac that is very cheap to 
register, but blows away every thing else.  Really superb software.



