<TITLE> Application of Library Policy</TITLE>
<H1><IMG SRC="/CAF/cafnews.gif"> 
The Application of Library Intellectual Freedom Policies to Public and
Academic Computer Facilities (or "The Sermon in the Loop")
</h1><p>
by Carl M. Kadie (kadie@eff.org)<p>
For <i> Computers, Freedom, and Privacy '94</i><p>
Version 1 (corrections requested)<p>

<A Name="Contents"><h2>Contents</h2></a>
<ul>
<li><A HREF="#Resources">Resources</a>
<li><A HREF="#Introduction">Introduction</a>
<li><A href="#Resources">Resources</a>
<li><A href="#Introduction">Introduction</a>
<li><A href="#TopPolicies">Top Library Intellectual Freedom Policies</a>
<li><A href="#Disclaimers">Disclaimers</a>
<li><A href="#NYX">The Parable of NYX</a>
<li><A href="#CICA">The Parable of CICA</a>
<li><A href="#greek">The Parable of the Greek List</a>
<li><A href="#freenet">The Parable of the Freenet</a>
<li><A href="#iastate">The Parable of Iowa State University</a>
<li><A href="#vchip">The Parable of the V-Chip</a>
<li><A href="#cert">The Parable of CERT</a>
<li><A href="#k12">The Parable of K-12</a>
<li><A href="#Conclusion">Conclusion</a>
<li><A href="#Appendix1">Appendix 1 - More on the analogy</a>
</ul>

<A Name="Resources"><h2>Resources</h2></a>

This document is available via WWW/Mosiac from the <A
HREF="http://www.eff.org/CAF/">CAF Archive</a> as <A
HREF="http://www.eff.org/CAF/cfp94.kadie.html">
http://www.eff.org/CAF/cfp94.kadie.html</a>. The plain
text version is <A HREF="ftp://ftp.eff.org/pub/CAF/statements/cfp94.kadie">
ftp://ftp.eff.org/pub/CAF/statements/cfp94.kadie</a>.<p>
<p>

Via gopher as
<pre>
  gopher 1/CAF gopher.eff.org
</pre>
then select "Academic Freedom Statements" and "Application of
Library Policy to Computers". Also see "Library Policy Statements"<p>

Via anonymous ftp to ftp.eff.org, directory /pub/CAF/statements, file
cfp94.kadie. Other files of possible interest are /pub/CAF/README and
/pub/CAF/caf and /pub/CAF/library/README.<p>

For email access, send email to ftpmail@decwrl.dec.com. Include the
lines:
<pre>
  connect ftp.eff.org
  get caf
  get README
  cd  /pub/CAF/statements
  get cfp94.kadie
</pre><p>

<A Name="Introduction"><h2>Introduction</h2></a>

I am a busybody. I hear about a student apparently losing her Netnews
access at Columbia U. because she wrote, in a public forums, "stop
fucking with his email" or I hear about a university that bans
"alt.censorship" and all other newsgroups with names starting with
"alt." because someone was offended by the public display of sexually
explicit computer picture and I want to do something about it.<p>

<i>some references:</i>
<ul>
<li> <a href="ftp://ftp.eff.org/pub/CAF/news/mar_20_1994">news/mar_20_1994</a>
<li> <a href="ftp://ftp.eff.org/pub/CAF/news/nov_14_1993">news/nov_14_1993</a>
</ul>

I usually document, criticize, and publicize. Sometimes, things are
put right, sometimes nothing happens except that others become for
sensitive to the issues. I often get email saying "thanks". Sometimes
I get angry email that says "Who died and left you God?".<p>

Let me state here and now, I don't claim to be God. Everyone knows
that the god of intellectual freedom is Dr. Judith Krug, Director of
the American Library Association's Office for Intellectual Freedom. At
most, I fancy myself as merely her son.<p>

The question of how the information superhighway will effect libraries
is an interesting one. I'm not going to talk about it. Instead I'm
going to talk about my experience applying the intellectual freedom
policy developed to libraries to computer facilities. In the terms of
the analogy, I'm going to talk about applying the Old Testament (or
Tulmud) to the Gentiles.<p>

(<A HREF="#Appendix1">Appendix 1 contains more on this analogy.</a>)<p>

The format of this "Sermon in the Loop" is straightforward. First,
I'll list the Library Intellectual Freedom Policies that I reference
most often. Then I'll given little case studies (or should that be
"parables"?) that illustrate their application to computer facilities.
The case studies are drawn from real incidents and references are
available. Finally, I'll talk about what you can do.<p>

I hope that after this talk, you will know where to look for some
answers to questions you may have related to intellectual freedom.<p>

