<HEAD>
<TITLE>A Tribute to Phil Zimmermann</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFDD" TEXT=#060E73 LINK=#AB0DB5 VLINK=#0D7734 ALINK="00FF00">
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER> NorthStar</H1>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>A Guiding Light on Internet Issues<BR> Newsletter of the
<A HREF="http://www.iuc.org/www/molsen/">Internet Users
Consortium</A><BR>
********************************************************</H3>
<P>
<STRONG>NorthStar</STRONG> is a guiding light to help you focus on the
issues which threaten our Internet Freedom. <STRONG>We sincerely invite
your participation</STRONG> at any level, from discussion to action.
Rethink what Activism means - Isn't it just participation?<BR>
<HR>
<STRONG>NorthStar #9 &#160; Sunday 1/21/96<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:proteios@iuc.org">Director..........proteios@iuc.org</A><BR>
<A HREF="mailto:wtj@primenet.com">Editor..............wtj@primenet.com</A></STRONG>
<HR>
<b>Update:   Internet Users Consortium</b> <br>
Internet Users Consortium has a made a Public Service Announcement it is sending to radio stations in Oregon for the Senate election. We are considering refining and running this PSA on the radio in other areas to cross the barrier between the well-informed Internet population and the large number of less aware, non-users. The PSA promotes the Internet as a form of Telecommunication whose only limitations are those we place on it. It has a very positive message and includes a phone number for people to call for further information.
<P>
<STRONG>NEVER SAY NEVER . . . but . . .</STRONG><BR>
We at NorthStar believe so strongly in these principles that we make<BR>
the following pledge to you, our reader and fellow Internet Activist:<BR>
<STRONG>NorthStar will NEVER sell/rent/trade/share our mailing list<BR>
NorthStar will NEVER use Government mandated encryption<BR>
NorthStar will NEVER represent any commercial interest<BR>
NorthStar will NEVER cooperate with any Government intrusion<BR></STRONG>
<HR></P>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>PHIL ZIMMERMANN - An American Hero</H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
Civilization is the progress toward a society of privacy. The savage's whole existence is public, ruled by the laws of his tribe. Civilization is the process of setting man free from men. &#160; <br><STRONG>Ayn Rand - The Fountainhead (1943)</STRONG>
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>There's no better way to introduce the altruistic Net.hero, Phil Zimmermann, than by quoting his own words from, <A HREF="http://www.ifi.uio.no/~staalesc/PGP/why_PGP.shtml"><STRONG>"Why Do You Need PGP?"</STRONG></A>:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<STRONG>It's personal. It's private. And it's no one's business but yours. You may be planning a political campaign, discussing your taxes, or having an illicit affair. Or you may be doing something that you feel shouldn't be illegal, but is. Whatever it is, you don't want your private electronic mail or confidential documents read by anyone else. There's nothing wrong with asserting your privacy. Privacy is as apple-pie as the Constitution.<BR><BR>

More and more of our private communications are being routed through electronic channels. Electronic mail is gradually replacing conventional paper mail. E-mail messages are just too easy to intercept and scan for interesting keywords. This can be done easily, routinely, automatically, and undetectably on a grand scale.<BR><BR>

If privacy is outlawed, only outlaws will have privacy. Intelligence agencies have access to good cryptographic technology. So do the big arms and drug traffickers. So do defense contractors, oil companies, and other corporate giants. But ordinary people and grassroots political organizations mostly have not had access to affordable military grade public-key cryptographic technology. Until now. PGP empowers people to take their privacy into their own hands. There's a growing social need for it. That's why I wrote PGP.</STRONG><BR><BR>

<EM>Note: Phil Zimmermann took several months off his regular consulting job in Boulder, Colorado to write PGP and then he gave the program away free of charge on Internet.</EM>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
The following, which reveals a bit more about PZ and PGP, is exerpted from <A HREF="http://www.isyshu.net/hol/hol5.htm"> <STRONG>an essay by Steven Carlson:</STRONG></A><BLOCKQUOTE>Phillip Zimmermann (PZ) doesn't look much like a revolutionary. A smallish, paunchy sort of guy, with beard and glasses, Phil looks more like a math major. In fact he's a cryptographer, which is more or less the same thing. <STRONG>Zimmermann unintentionally made himself famous by writing, and giving away for free, a powerful encryption program called PGP</STRONG> - short for "Pretty Good Privacy."<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Phil's revolutionary act was to let his PGP software loose on the Internet</STRONG> where it spread "like dandilion seeds on the wind" copied from computer to computer across the global network of networks. This act started a very political movement for privacy on the Internet, and earned Zimmermann the wrath of the US government.<BR><BR>

Governments and private companies already have the computer power necessary to scan great volumes of email for keywords. Soon, PZ thinks, we will be able to scan the international phone traffic for individual voice prints. And cellular phone conversations are already notoriously easy to intercept. Recognizing this, the US government has been moving to set standards for voice and data encryption. The government, however, doesn't want unbreakable codes. The government says it should be able to listen in when necessary for purposes of law enforcement.<BR><BR>

PZ doesn't see any reason to trust governments. He points to the Nixon administration's wide-scale surviellence of anti-war activitist in the 1970's. <STRONG>"The wrong techonology infrastructure could allow a future government to watch every move anyone makes to oppose it," he says. "It could very well be the last goverment we ever elect."</STRONG><BR><BR>

By setting the technological standard for encryption, the US government could practically ensure that all encryption has a police "back door." <STRONG>So PZ decided to act first. He released his free PGP software in 1991, hoping it would raise public awareness and preempt the government's standard</STRONG>.<BR><BR>

<STRONG>In doing so, he raised the ire of US authorities who want to control that technology. But PZ is unrepentant</STRONG>. He's proud that his software is now available world-wide. He says he's received email from dissidents fighting the anti-democratic military regime in Burma who use PGP to protect their communications. During Boris Yeltsin's battle with the Russian Parliament last year, PZ received a message from Latvia: "If dictatorship takesover Russia, Your PGP is widespread from Baltic to Far East now and will help democratic people if necessary. Thanks."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<STRONG>***Phil Zimmermann***<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.ifi.uio.no/~staalesc/PGP/why_PGP.shtml">Phil's Own Words, "Why Do You Need PGP?"</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.isyshu.net/hol/hol5.htm">An Essay by Steven Carlson from Hungary Online</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.netresponse.com/zldf/whyitmatters.html">Why All This Matters</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/wired/1.6/departments/electric.word.html">Just when you thought it was safe to encrypt again...</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.research.umbc.edu/~warr/cryptart.html">Mike Godwin's Crypto Conundrum</A><BR>
</STRONG>
<HR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Cut To The Chase</H3>
<P>On April 10, 1991, shortly after the Gulf War, one single email message from Bill Murray (WHMurray@DOCKMASTER.NCSC.MIL), then a computer-security consultant to the NSA, shocked the entire Net.community. His msg. warned about the following sentence buried in the now-infamous Senate Bill 266, the "Anti-Terrorism" bill authored by Senator Biden and Arizona's <EM>beloved</EM> <STRONG>:-)</STRONG> Sen. DeConcini:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<STRONG>"It is the sense of Congress that providers of electronic communications services and manufacturers of electronic communications service equipment shall ensure that communications systems permit the government to obtain the plain text contents of voice, data, and other communications when appropriately authorized by law."</STRONG></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>

Mr. Murray's msg. ended with the following Patrick Henrylike sentences:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
"In the United States the people, not the Congress, are sovereign; it should not be illegal for the people to have access to communications that the government cannot read. We should be free from unreasonable search and seizure; we should be free from self-incrimination. <STRONG>The government already has powerful tools of investigation at its disposal; it has demonstrated precious little restraint in their use</STRONG>.<BR><BR>

"Any assertion that all use of any such trap-doors would be only 'when appropriately authorized by law' is absurd on its face. It is not humanlypossible to construct a mechanism that could meet that requirement; any such mechanism would be subject to abuse. <STRONG>I suggest that you begin to stock up on crypto gear while you can still get it.</STRONG>"
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>The Net went ballistic over this Orwellian mandate. One propellor-head in particular, <STRONG>Kelly Goen</STRONG>, resident of the San Francisco Bay area, was so outraged by the implications of S266, which would outlaw PGP, that he went on a Paul Reverelike ride, as described in <A HREF="http://www-hsc.usc.edu/~quan/jim1.htm"><STRONG>Jim Warren's article, "The Persecution of Phil Zimmermann, American"</STRONG></A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<STRONG>On a weekend around the first of June, 1991, Kelly Goen began uploading complete PGP to systems around the U.S.</STRONG> He called several times, probably because I had organized the recently-completed First Conference on Computers, Freedom & Privacy, or maybe because of my comments on the net critical of S266, telling me his progress.<BR><BR>

<STRONG>He was driving around the Bay Area with a laptop, acoustic coupler and a cellular phone. He would stop at a pay-phone; upload a number of copies for a few minutes, then disconnect and rush off to another phone miles away. He said he wanted to get as many copies of PGP scattered to as many BBSs and host-computers around the United States as possible before the government could get an injunction and stop him</STRONG>. I thought he was being rather paranoid. In light of the following persecution of PZ, perhaps Goen was just being realistic.<BR><BR>

<STRONG>About two years after the PGP uploads, the government began threatening to prosecute PZ for illegal trafficking in munitions - cryptography. [He was first visited by U.S. Customs agents on Feb. 17, 1993.] For more than two years, they have been investigating whether he "exported" PGP</STRONG>. It appears at press-time that they will probably prosecute him.<BR><BR>

I cry for what Phil Zimmermann must be going through. He had little financial resources to begin with; this has already cost him, dearly. For almost two years, he has been under the horrifying threat of wasting all of his assets including his home, just to defend himself against the outrageous abuse of a federal government that will go to any expense to 'win'.<BR><BR>

All because he dared to write a cryptographic program that the government couldn't crack, that someone else made available to U.S. citizens. If there is any justice remaining in this nation, this screams out for immediate redress!
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<STRONG>Happily and Surprisingly, the US Govt dropped its case against PZ on 1/8/96</STRONG> as explained in <A HREF="http://www.netresponse.com/zldf/"><STRONG>A Letter from Phil Zimmermann</STRONG></A>. More good news comes in the form of an award. <STRONG>Philip R. Zimmermann has been awarded The 1995 Chrysler Award of Innovation in Design for Pretty Good Privacy (PGP)</STRONG>. Sponsored by the Chrysler Corporation, the Chrysler Award of Innovation in Design was presented on August 15th at the new San Francisco Museum of Modern Art. <STRONG>This program recognizes "socially responsible, cutting edge individuals and companies reaching beyond the traditional boundaries of design disciplines"</STRONG>.</P>
<P>
<A HREF="mailto:prz@acm.org"><STRONG>Perhaps Phil would appreciate a word or two</A> of congratulation and encouragement</STRONG>.</P>
<HR>
<STRONG>***Phil Zimmermann***<BR>
<A HREF="http://www-hsc.usc.edu/~quan/jim1.htm">Jim Warren's article, "The Persecution of Phil Zimmermann, American"</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://world.std.com/~franl/privacy/parable.html">Perry's Privacy Parable</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.netresponse.com/zldf/">A Letter from Phil Zimmermann</A><BR>

