<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Telecommunications Attack of 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#E9FEF6 TEXT=#022B4B LINK=#F5050F VLINK=#0807CE
ALINK=#0807CE>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER> NorthStar</H1>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>A Guiding Light on Internet Issues<BR> Newsletter of the
<A HREF="http://www.iuc.org/www/molsen/">Internet Users
Consortium</A><BR>
********************************************************</H3> <P>
<STRONG>NorthStar</STRONG> is a guiding light to help you focus on the
issues which threaten our Internet Freedom. <STRONG>We sincerely invite
your participation</STRONG> at any level, from discussion to action.
Rethink what Activism means - Isn't it just participation?<BR> <HR>
<STRONG>
NorthStar #10      Sunday 2/4/96
<BR> <A HREF="mailto:proteios@iuc.org"> Director..........proteios@iuc.org</A><BR> <A
HREF="mailto:wtj@primenet.com">Editor..............wtj@primenet.com</A>
<BR> <A
HREF="mailto:molsen@iuc.org">Contributor.....molsen@iuc.org</a><br>
</STRONG>
<HR>
<b>Update:   Internet Users Consortium</b> <br>

Individuals and Organizations have involved themselves in actions ranging from open protest to outright civil disobedience. The <b>Blue Ribbon</b> campaign by the EFF, black background colors on webpages and email/Usenet signatures containing Bible quotes, swears and anti-censorship slogans are among the forms of protest that are being brandished by Internet users in an attempt to show their disgust at our governments abusive and negligent treatment of Internet issues. <b>Government will conform the Global telco networks to fit their style of regulation and NOT the other way around.</b><br>  Unity and solidarity. <b>Internet users need to come together and protest as per our Rights.</b><br><p>
<HR>
<STRONG>NEVER SAY NEVER . . . but . . .</STRONG><BR> We at NorthStar
believe so strongly in these principles that we make<BR> the following
pledge to you, our reader and fellow Internet Activist:<BR> <STRONG>
NorthStar will NEVER sell/rent/trade/share our mailing list<BR> NorthStar
will NEVER use Government mandated encryption<BR> NorthStar will NEVER
represent any commercial interest<BR> NorthStar will NEVER cooperate with
any Government intrusion<BR> </STRONG>
<HR></P>
<H2 ALIGN =CENTER>The Telecommunications Attack of 1996</H2></CENTER><P>
<P>
<STRONG>The Telecommunications Attack of 1996 has passed the House and Senate</STRONG> [by obscenely overwhelming margins] and is ready for President Clinton's promised signature.  As much as we needed a new Telecom Bill to replace the old law, which was passed in 1934, we did not need a new law which overtly promotes monopoly/oligopoly formation in the Entertainment/Information/Communications Industry. Nor did we need a new law which tramples the First Amendment by criminalizing speech which is perfectly acceptable in other forums. Nor did we need a new law which bans discussion of Abortion on Internet. The heartfelt words of <A HREF="mailto: joeshea@netcom.com"><STRONG> 
Joe Shea</STRONG></A>, Editor-in-Chief of <A HREF="http://www.newshare.com/Reporter/"> <STRONG>The American Reporter</STRONG></A> are worth a moment's reflection:</P>
 
<BLOCKQUOTE><STRONG>Frankly, the thing I feel deepest about the passage of the telecommunications act is hurt.  Perhaps anger underlies that, but I don't think so. The hurt starts way deep down in my gut, where the things we believe most deeply sleep. I believe in America, its people and its Constitution, and I know -- no matter how many times we're told how wonderful this telecommunications bill is -- that our faith in the leadership of Congress has been betrayed.</STRONG></BLOCKQUOTE></P>
<P>
Predictably, our Media-Elite made little if any mention in their news coverage [why am I not surprised?] of the despicable Section 507 of the Telecom Bill, which bans all online discussions of abortion <STRONG>[try to imagine that, folks! AN INTELLIGENT ONLINE DISCUSSION OF ABORTION IS NOW ILLEGAL!!!]</STRONG> nor did they dwell on other Sections which bar other types of online discussion, which may violate an undefined [could we say, "indefinable"?] standard of "decency". This is the same double-standard of {morality} which was applied to other "new" media (movies, radio, TV) in their first few years of existence due to popular fears of the unknown based on ignorance and scare stories circulated by the "old" media.</P>
<P>
Ironically, the same ban does not apply to the telecommunications moguls' television, cable and telephone corporations, though. In fact, the Big 3 -- Time-Warner, News Corporation and General Electric or Westinghouse, which own NBC and CBS -- will control all of the information delivered via television, cable, newspaper and the Internet. Naturally, once the "good" people gain control the Net, the absurd restrictions on free speech contained in the Telecom Bill will be challenged and defeated. <STRONG><EM>Could these restrictions possibly be a ploy to help eliminate the 2000 or so pesky [hard to control/independent] Internet Service Providers??? Is it entirely accidental that only the ISP's with deep pockets could afford the costs of reviewing every byte of data which passes thru their server in search of "indecent" speech lest they be fined for violation of the new Telecom Law???</EM></STRONG></P>
<P>
<STRONG>Here is an excerpt from the official statement by <A HREF="http://www.eff.org/pub/Alerts/cda_020296_eff.statement">The Electronic Frontier Foundation:</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Congress demonstrates once more their willingness to abandon their most
sacred responsibilities - the protection of the US Constitution and
Bill of Rights - in order to expedite legislation that sacrifices 
individual, family and community rights in its rush to win the support 
of telecom industry giants as well as the religious right, during an 
election year.<BR>

Consider this a wake-up call.  Our elected officials have spoken, and 
with the passage of the most sweeping US telecommunications legislation 
in over 60 years, our Constitutional rights in the new medium
of computer networking have been usurped.  As the 21st century draws near,
our elected representatives have chosen to take us back to the close of 
the 19th.<BR>

The consolation offered by our elected officials to those concerned about
abridging free speech, is that there is a high probability that the
censorship provisions in this bill would not stand up to court challenges
based on constitutional grounds.</BLOCKQUOTE></STRONG>
<P>
As many know, the <STRONG>ACLU</STRONG> has plans to challenge the law the minute the
first arrest occurs.  The <A HREF="http://www.newshare.com/Reporter/"><STRONG>American Reporter</A> and a Judge</STRONG> have openly stated that they will not comply with this misguided legislation. Many other activists are putting Bible verses that are <STRONG><EM>indecent</EM></STRONG>, the 7 Dirty Words, etc., in an act of <STRONG>Civil Disobedience</STRONG> which threatens to reach a scale reminiscent of  the open protests of the 60s.
Take for example, the <a href="http://www.webcom.com/~ezundel/english/">Zundelsites</a>.  A government tried to shut it down, and when they did, 10 people mirrored the site.  Now its the hottest free speech issue on the Net right now. It challenges us to think about all the forms of speech we defend. Even though they didn't necessarily agree with the content, they did it for free speech on-line. As Voltaire said, 
<BLOCKQUOTE><STRONG>I may not agree with what you say, but I will defend to the death your right to say it!"</STRONG></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><HR>
<STRONG>***The Telecommunications Attack of 1996***<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.newshare.com/Reporter/">The American Reporter</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.eff.org/">Electronic Frontier Foundation</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.aclu.org/">ACLU</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.eff.org/~rmt/ban.html">Banned Websites</A><BR>
<a href="http://www.webcom.com/~ezundel/english/">Zundelsites</a><BR>
</strong>
<HR>
<p>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Online Services &#160; <EM>This is a Service??</EM></H3></CENTER>
While the on-line censorship is one problem that we face, another larger issue confronts us.  The Telecommunications Attack of 1996 has the ability to create monopolies that could severely restrict our options for Internet connection, service and quality. The large corporations replacing the smaller ISP's and issuing AOL-like restrictions on speech would be much more controllable and susceptible to the whims of special interest groups like the Christian Coalition that demand complete sterilization of the Internet.  <STRONG>AOL</STRONG> is currently censoring original poetry by its members.</P>
<P>
But in another example of online unity, a band of members got together and decided to fight the censorship.  <STRONG>AOL</STRONG> went so far as to remove the word <STRONG><EM>breast</EM></STRONG>, much to the displeasure of a <STRONG>Breast Cancer Survivors Group</STRONG> who were involved in group therapy via <STRONG>AOL</STRONG>. The group was cut off for a period of time because they had the audacity to use the word <STRONG><EM>breast </EM></STRONG> when describing a body part. Oh yeah, the word has an anatomical  meaning as well.</P>
<P>
Chew on this. Bowing to legal the innuendoes of a judge in Germany, <STRONG>Compuserve</STRONG> immediately removed all newsgroups with words that the Germans found offensive. No objection. No plea for time. No explanation that this is an International Forum. No backbone. No nothing. Just <STRONG>CAVE!</STRONG> The dictators of the world are watching events like these. The dictators of the world fear and loathe the Internet. Once they see how EZ it is to bully the online services, they will be incessant in their demands for control over Internet within their borders. <STRONG>The rest of the world is watching the US Legislature to see how the US govt handles this <EM>threatening</EM> Internet thing, because we're really the only ones w/ the "CONGRESS SHALL MAKE NO LAW ......" type of Constitution, so if WE wont defend free speech on the Net then why should they?</STRONG></P>
<P>
<STRONG>Compuserve</STRONG> used word searches to remove groups with certain names.  In their haste, they removed a clari.news.gay. These actions show just how dangerous monopolistic entities can be. The CyberQueer Lounge was adversely effected by this.  It is our position that these monopolies are inevitable under the new Telecom Bill.  We may be forced into AOL type services with very little in civil liberties.  But exactly what can we do?  That is something that we will have to figure out.  Nobody wants each email transaction known, like each financial transaction already is to the IRS.  It's the best way to regulate the Net.  Put us all on heavily moderated online services. That hurts.</P>
<P>
In upcoming issues of <A HREF="http://www.indirect.com/www/proteios/northstar.html"><STRONG>NorthStar</STRONG></A>, we will examine the strategies that activists are taking in response to Draconian forms of censorship employed by major on-line services.  Some choose to elicit help from court challenges, corporate support or by speaking their case to the Internet and increasing awareness by telling their stories to us all.</P>
<P>
The Internet is like the mythical Hydra.  Cut off one of its heads and two grow back. Yet they will try to strangle us to control us. Trust me. They will. Censor one individual, and 10 more will spring up carrying the same documents or mirror sites.   
These responses should be applauded.  Things are happening quickly and these displays of unity are enlightening and inspiring.  Free speech is more important than ideology.  If one lets another be silenced, it is only a matter of time before he himself is silenced.</P> 
<P>
The Electronic Freedom Foundation is sponsoring <A HREF="http://www.eff.org/blueribbon.html"><STRONG>The Blue Ribbon Campaign for Online Freedom of Speech</STRONG></A>. A blue ribbon is chosen as the symbol for the preservation of basic civil rights in the electronic world. Since these rights are so clearly at-risk, all Internet users are strongly encouraged to place a blue ribbon graphic on their servers, their home pages, etc. A variety of blue ribbon graphics are available for the download at the above EFF URL.</P> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<STRONG>When they took the fourth amendment, I was silent because I don't deal drugs. When they took the sixth amendment, I kept quiet because I know I'm innocent. When they took the second amendment, I said nothing because I don't own a gun. Now they've come for the first amendment, and I can't say anything at all. <A HREF="mailto:tsf@cs.cmu.edu">Tim Freeman</A></STRONG></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><HR>

<STRONG>***The Telecommunications Attack of 1996***<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.eff.org/blueribbon.html">The Blue Ribbon Campaign for Online Freedom of Speech</A><BR>
