<TITLE>NorthStar - 12/10/95 - Key Escrow Encryption (Intro)</TITLE> </HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFDD" TEXT=#060E73 LINK=#AB0DB5 VLINK=#0D7734
ALINK="00FF00">
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER> NorthStar</H1>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>A Guiding Light on Internet Issues<BR> Newsletter of the
<A HREF="http://www.indirect.com/www/molsen/">Internet Users
Consortium</A><BR>
********************************************************</H3> <P>
<STRONG>NorthStar</STRONG> is a guiding light to help you focus on the
issues which threaten our Internet Freedom. <STRONG>We sincerely invite
your participation</STRONG> at any level, from discussion to action.
Rethink what Activism means - Isn't it just participation?<BR> <HR>
<STRONG>
NorthStar #6 &#160;   Sunday 12/10/95<BR> <A HREF="mailto:proteios@indirect.com"> Director..........proteios@indirect.com</A><BR> <A
HREF="mailto:wtj@primenet.com">Editor..............wtj@primenet.com</A>
</STRONG>
<HR>
<b>Update:   Internet Users Consortium</b> <br>
Get details about the <a href="http://www.hotwired.com/staff/digaman">Internet Protest Rally</a><br>

The current threat to Internet Freedom from maligned government legislation reminds us all to question our beliefs and make a strong decision on where we stand in terms of our freedom and our future.<p>
<STRONG>We would like to make vocal our commitment to Internet Freedom for every Internet User. NEVER SAY NEVER . . . but . . .</STRONG><BR> We at NorthStar
believe so strongly in these principles that we make<BR> the following
pledge to you, our reader and fellow Internet Activist:<BR> <STRONG>
NorthStar will NEVER sell/rent/trade/share our mailing list<BR> NorthStar
will NEVER use Government mandated encryption<BR> NorthStar will NEVER
represent any commercial interest<BR> NorthStar will NEVER cooperate with
any Government intrusion<BR> </STRONG>
<HR></P>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>KEY-ESCROW ENCRYPTION (Intro)</H2> <P>
We're all hearing quite a bit about the term, "Key Escrow" or "Key Escrow
Encryption" or "Public-Key Encryption", recently. <STRONG>Public-Key Encryption</STRONG> (of
whatever flavor - Key Escrow, Clipper, PGP, RSA, DES, or other) <STRONG>is
THE #1 MOST IMPORTANT ISSUE REGARDING THE FUTURE OF
INTERNET</STRONG>.</P>
<P>
More than bandwidth, more than the price of access, more than the
information haves vs. the information have-nots, more than browser bells
and whistles, more than virtual reality, more than any other aspect of
networked computering, <STRONG>Encryption will determine the future of
Internet and the future of Internet will determine the future of
humanity</STRONG>.</P> <P>
More and more of our personal information (medical, financial, legal, you
name it) is being transmitted and stored on computer networks. Soon, even
our money will be just another digital transmission. No one doubts that the
continued functioning of human society depends on absolute network
security. No one doubts that Encryption is the key to such security.
However, <STRONG>battle lines are being drawn over Encryption
standards</STRONG>.</P> <P>
Since there seems to be major confusion on all sides as to the actual
meaning and the real implications of Encryption, NorthStar launches, w/
this issue, a Four Part Series dedicated to Key Escrow Encryption. This
issue serves as an Introduction to Encryption.</P> <P>
We'll skip the War Stories which usually accompany introductory
explanations of Encryption, but be informed that Cryptography has played a
decisive role in every war in recorded history. Encryption has always been
associated w/ spies, and spook organizations like Army Intelligence (sic),
CIA or NSA, and bound up w/ National Security. This is one reason the
average citizen has never known much about Encryption.</P>
<P>
Another reason Jane Q. Public has never become fascinated w/ the study of
modern Encryption is that it is Industrial Strength Mathematics. Those of
us who struggled with high school algebra can forget about understanding
the math invoved in Cryptography, but <STRONG>anyone can follow the basic
principles if they are properly explained</STRONG>.</P> <P>
Modern Cryptography began in the mid-70's with Whitfield Diffie's
formulation of the "Public-Key Cryptosystem", which uses two keys (a public
key and a private key) and the publication of the RAS algorithm, which uses
mathematically scrambled messages based on large prime numbers. To break
one single message encrypted with these mathematical codes and two keys
would require <STRONG>US$BILLIONS and thousands of years of supercomputer
time</STRONG>.</P>
<P>
All prior Encryption schemes relied upon one key (a code book), which, once
obtained, allowed anyone to read all messages sent using that particular
code. Whereas, Public-Key Encryption uses two keys, a public key which
everyone can have and a private key, which is a secret key. <STRONG>Here's
how it works......</STRONG></P>
<HR>
<STRONG>*** KEY-ESCROW ENCRYPTION (Intro) ***<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.eff.org/pub/Privacy/Key_escrow/">EFF
"Privacy-Crypto-Key Escrow" Archive</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.quadralay.com/www/Crypt/">Quadralay's Cryptography Archive
</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.epic.org/crypto/CKE/">Commercial Key Escrow</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.oberlin.edu/~brchkind/cyphernomicon/9.html">Policy:
Clipper,Key Escrow, and Digital Telephony</a><br></STRONG>
<HR>
<P>
Joe and Jane want to exchange 100% private messages via computer. Joe has
Jane's public-key and Jane has Joe's public-key. Obviously, they both hold
their own secret key. OK now, Joe sends a message to Jane using her
public-key to encrypt it. This, in effect, puts <STRONG>A LOCK</STRONG> on
the message and there's <STRONG>ONLY ONE KEY IN THE WORLD</STRONG> (Jane's
private-key) which will unlock it.</P>
<P>
If Joe adds <STRONG>A SECOND LOCK</STRONG> to the message (his private-key)
then the only person in the world who can unlock it would be Jane (w/ her
private-key) and and the only person in the world who could have sent it
would be Joe, because only his public key will unlock the message. Thus,
Jane can see <STRONG>Joe's digital signature</STRONG>.</P> <P>
The FBI/NSA/CIA/IRS/Fill in the Blank with your favorite Govt Acronym/
became more than a little concerned at the theoretical possibilty of
Unbreakable Transmissions, but such Encryption schemes were extremely
difficult to use as was the Internet in the 80's, so not to worry. This all
changed in 1991, when <STRONG>Phil Zimmermann released on Internet
(free-of-charge) his gift to humanity, PGP (Pretty Good
Privacy)</STRONG>.</P> <P>
Suddenly, any bozo w/ a computer and an Internet connection could send and
receive absolutely unbreakable coded messages, i.e., the Govt could not
read the messages. Digital telephones would offer the same level of
privacy, i.e., No Wiretaps! This has spooked the spooks. Worst-case
scenario for them. <STRONG>The Govt has sworn that it will regain control
of the situation</STRONG>.</P>
<P>
Beginning w/ Senate Bill 266 (The Digital Telephony Bill) which was
defeated, we have seen Son of S266 (The Clipper Chip) which was defeated,
and now Son of Clipper (Key Escrow Encryption). All of these legislative
proposals have the same goal - to assure that the Govt has access to any
digital transmission at any time. <STRONG>The threat to our privacy and the
potential for abuse make Key Escrow Encryption the most frightening
Government Surveillance Tool to come down the pike since Big Brother's
Telescreen</STRONG>. (To be Continued...)</P>
<HR>
<STRONG>*** KEY-ESCROW ENCRYPTION (Intro) ***<BR> <A
HREF="http://www-swiss.ai.mit.edu/6095/articles/froomkin-metaphor/text.html"
>The Metaphor is the Key</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/clipper/diffie.html">Key Escrow:
Its Impact and Alternatives
</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.indirect.com/www/molsen/library.html">Internet Users
Consortium Archives</A><BR>
