<HEAD>
<TITLE>NorthStar - 1/7/96 - Key Escrow Encryption (Intro)</TITLE> </HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFDD" TEXT=#060E73 LINK=#AB0DB5 VLINK=#0D7734
ALINK="00FF00">
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER> NorthStar</H1>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>A Guiding Light on Internet Issues<BR> Newsletter of the
<A HREF="http://www.iuc.org/www/molsen/">Internet Users
Consortium</A><BR>
********************************************************</H3> <P>
<STRONG>NorthStar</STRONG> is a guiding light to help you focus on the
issues which threaten our Internet Freedom. <STRONG>We sincerely invite
your participation</STRONG> at any level, from discussion to action.
Rethink what Activism means - Isn't it just participation?<BR> <HR>
<STRONG>
NorthStar  #8    Sunday 1/7/96
<BR> <A HREF="mailto:proteios@indirect.com"> Director..........proteios@indirect.com</A><BR> <A
HREF="mailto:molsen@indirect.com">Editor..............molsen@indirect.com</A>
</STRONG>
<HR>
<b>Update:   Internet Users Consortium</b> <br>

The Homepage is nearing completion and we would like everyone to drop by and offer suggestions, utilize its functions or just look on in amazement. It has all the links and integration needed by individual activists and grassroots organizations. We have made it in this style for efficient coordinated strategies and effective communications between us all. Try it at <a href="http://www.iuc.org/www/molsen/">http://www.iuc.org/www/molsen/</a><br>
<b>Notice the new domain name.</b>
<p>
<STRONG>NEVER SAY NEVER . . . but . . .</STRONG><BR> We at NorthStar
believe so strongly in these principles that we make<BR> the following
pledge to you, our reader and fellow Internet Activist:<BR> <STRONG>
NorthStar will NEVER sell/rent/trade/share our mailing list<BR> NorthStar
will NEVER use Government mandated encryption<BR> NorthStar will NEVER
represent any commercial interest<BR> NorthStar will NEVER cooperate with
any Government intrusion<BR> </STRONG>
<HR></P>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>
Compiled History of Cryptography
</H2> <P>
Daddy ... if your data is your own property, does it become less your property after you encrypt it?'' [Speaker at the NIST workshop, quoting his young son]. This and similar concerns have evolved symbiotically with the growth of modern encryption.  Many believe that cryptography was an outgrowth of government and their sole domain until the public key revolution in the 1970s. In truth, cryptography was invented over 3000 years ago by civilians. Its use ranges from Socrates and Plato to avoid persecution by the Church, to the ever-present coded languages of the military.  Remember 'One if by land, two if by sea'? You guessed it - civilian encryption.
<p>
The primary difference between civilian and government encryption is that government based crypto-analysis is dependent upon the their ability to intercept communications. And one needs to intercept an encrypted message in order to do crypto-analysis.
<p>
Civilian cryptology is comprised of finding strengths and weaknesses in new inventive applications. The desire is usually more personal in nature than one of surveillance or eavesdropping (like the government agenda).
<p>
In spite of the long history of civilians inventing new coding methods and
governments learning how to break them, the US government is now opposed to civilians' having access to and creating strong methods of encryption. So despite the fact that we civilians have developed and used cryptography for 4500 years, we all wake up one morning to find that we have no right to continue to do so.  Here is the evolving story of Cryptography as it is used by individuals and strong-armed by government.
<p>
The first notable form of government sponsored encryption is the federal Data Encryption Standard (DES) developed by a joint effort between IBM and the NSA. This single-key form was designed to standardize the encryption being used by businesses. DES is currently the algorithm used to protect most electronic financial transactions between banks in the US. It is a symmetric cryptographic algorithm, which means that the same password, or "key", that is used to encrypt a message is also used to decrypt it. Export of DES is controlled by the State Department.
<p>
Critics of the DES algorithm charge that the key was designed to be long enough to frustrate corporate eavesdroppers, but short enough to be broken by the NSA. Others feared there might be a "back door," known as S-boxes, that would allow the agency to use computational shortcuts to break the code.
<p>
An example of this is given by Michael Wiener, who has published a paper containing a design to crack the DES code with a guaranteed solution in 7 hours.  His machine has a price tag of $1 million, but since trillions of dollars are protected by this code, a one million dollar investment is pocket change compared to the payoff.  This epitomizes the need for stronger encryption for computer data security.
<p>
A lone US company holds four primary patents relating to cryptography.  This includes the RSA algorithm (from the initials of its three developers). It has an 80-bit key, instead of DES's 56-bit key, making it approximately 16 million times as strong. This algorithm utilizes two keys instead of one.  A message encrypted with one key can only be decrypted by the other, and vice versa. This works well for things like e-mail, and solves most of the problems associated with key exchange in a symmetric cryptosystem.
<p>
Phil Zimmermann, a programmer, produced a program called "Pretty Good Privacy" (PGP), which uses RSA. Using PGP, I can send you one of my two keys (the "public" key) and keep my other key (the "private" key) secret. You send me your public key and keep your private key, well...private. I use your public key to encrypt messages, and you decode them with your private key. The public key can be given away to anyone; the private key is secretly yours, so it cannot be intercepted.
<p>
The forms of strong cryptography implemented by DES or RSA is classified as munitions according to US International Traffic in Arms Regulations (ITAR) export laws. Exporting a program like PGP outside of the US and Canada is considered a crime much like exporting nuclear warheads. <HR>
<STRONG>***History of Cryptography***<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/cme/html/timeline.html">Cryptography Timeline</a><br>
<A HREF="http://rschp2.anu.edu.au:8080/crypt.html">Cryptography and PGP Page</a><br>
<A HREF="http://www.dcs.ex.ac.uk/~aba/rsa/">export-a-crypto system sig</a><br>
<A HREF="http://www.hotwired.com/Lib/Privacy/index.html">HotWired's Index of Privacy Resources</a><br>
</strong>
<HR>
<P>
The FBI opposes encryption because it would make wiretapping and similar measures much more difficult, if not impossible. The only way to make encryption work for law enforcement purposes is to make it a mandatory, rather than a voluntary measure. In response to this, law enforcement decided to react by seeking legislation requiring that telephone networks and similar communications channels be designed in a way that facilitates wiretapping (recall that $500 million of your tax dollars are used to tap 1% of the phone lines). They have also designed and supported EES in the form of the Clipper Chip, which enables the government to keep a copy of the key needed to decrypt all communications. This is the advent of key escrow encryption.
<p>
Clipper was originally announced as the first element of a family of
hardware-based, government key escrow encryption devices that would meet the security needs for future voice and data communications. Even though Vice president Gore has commented that "...[T]he Clipper Chip is...for telephone communications and not for computer networks and video networks...".  The requirements of the business community for strong encryption caused the US government to propose the Escrowed Encryption Standard (EES), commonly referred to as the "Clipper Chip". This would be a strong cryptosystem based on a unique, classified algorithm (not RSA). To protect the secrecy of the algorithm, it would only be available in hardware form.
<p>
This presupposes that it is reasonable for the government to request, and even require, that individuals communicate in a manner that makes interception by the government possible.  This clashes with the Administrative Procedures Act (APA). Whereas, a victim of an illegal wiretap would have a cause of action under Title III against the wire tapper, there is no repercussions for the escrow agents if he acts negligently or didnt follow procedure. All this in the absence of congressional authorization. This policy cuts out the legislature, and indeed the public, from the decision to proceed with EES. So in essence, they have coerced the public by wielding federal market power to force an encryption standard without providing any real administrative accountability.
<p>
Many industry groups, civil liberties groups, and professional cryptographers objected to the implementation of a cryptosystem for which the US government held copies of all the keys.  Export restrictions on strong cryptographic software have been                     lifted for Clipper devices because of this.
<p>
If the government bars access to the keys by keeping them classified, then law enforcement officials won't be able to access them either. Many seem to have forgotten or are not aware that the Clipper program is not new, and it's also not the first time NSA has attempted to force communications security on U.S. industry.   
<p>
The new twist is access by key escrow.  Does the NSA truly believe they can evict other methods with EES?  There are over three million licensed RSA products currently in use in the U.S. today. So it is not likely they will succeed without creating significant problems.  The NSA has decided that the price is acceptable if U.S. industry and U.S. taxpayers bear these costs, no matter how outrageous. All this while simultaneously withholding the data from disclosure under the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA).  This policy was developed by unelected people who operate without oversight or accountability.  
<p>
The premise of the Clipper program was that the government could drive the market toward use of encryption products which incorporated government-based key escrow. The Administration is currently rethinking plans for data encryption standards leaving the Clipper a stranded technology.  No one wants to buy, or worse yet, standardize on, technology which has no means to upgrade.  As a long-run effort to force the market toward government-escrowed encryption standards, Clipper is a failure. 
<p>
The Clinton Administration declared the Clipper to be a 'voluntary' key escrow system. The FOIA determined that this was an outright lie. All experts claim the key escrow plan needs to be implemented as a mandatory measure if expected to work.
<p>
If law enforcement agencies were to be given the legal authority to succeed and therefore have absolute invasion of privacy, citizens would be required to stop attempting to keep communications private lest they accidentally succeed and therefore violate the agency's authority to have absolute understanding of any wiretapped conversation. 
<p>
So what now? How about civilian driven cryptography made by and for users with no government intervention. That makes the most sense and it violates no Rights. <HR>
<HR>
<STRONG>***History of Cryptography***<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/cme/html/civ-own-crypto.html">Civilian Ownership of Cryptography</a><br>
<A HREF="http://www.baker.com/grand-unification-theory/cryptography.html">Cryptography Brief of Grand Unification Theory</a><br>
<A HREF="http://www.iuc.org/www/molsen/library.html">Internet Users
Consortium Archives</A><BR>
