<h2> Newsletter of the <br><a href="http://www.indirect.com/www/molsen/index.html">Internet Users Consortium</a></h2>
<font size=4>
<p>
<hr align="right">
<p><b><a href="ftp://www.indirect.com/www/proteios/ns1">NorthStar #1 10/29/95</a></b> Online Activism is modern participation in government. Activism is not anti-government apathy is. Activism is playing a role in policy and law making.<p>
<b><a href="ftp://www.indirect.com/www/proteios/ns2">NorthStar #2 11/5/95</a></b> Escrow encryption or Escrow encroachment (of our privacy)? What gives our government the right to dictte the degree of privacy we experience. Is privacy a privilege or a right?<p>
<b><a href="ftp://www.indirect.com/www/proteios/ns3">NorthStar #3 11/12/95</a></b> The Telecommunications Bill spells Media concentration. Corporate viewpoints decrease what we know and how we respond. Who do we want to control these perspectives?<p>
<b><a href="ftp://www.indirect.com/www/proteios/ns4">NorthStar #4 11/19/95</a></b> Privacy may become an afforded luxury. If the average citizen doesnt speak up now he may never have this chance again. Its easier to prevent a law from being enacted then to repeal it once its in place.<p>
<b><a href="ftp://www.indirect.com/www/proteios/ns5">NorthStar #5 11/26/95</a></b> Current legislation may centralize power on the Internet. Centralizing power and control is anti-individual and exploits the Internet for personal power. We need to ensure a decentralized structure.
<p><b><font size=4>

</dl><p>

<b><A href="http://www.indirect.com/www/proteios/subs.html"><img border=0 align="left" src="sub.gif">Subscribe to Northstar</a></b><b><a href="http://www.indirect.com/www/molsen/index.html"><img border=0 src="iuc3ns.gif">Internet Users Consortium</a></b>

