<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Volunteer Who Wants To Make CGI Easy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = "FFFFFF" TEXT = "000000">

<CENTER>
This article mirrors the duplicate article in the August 5th issue 
of <A HREF = "http://www.webweek.com/">Web Week</A>

<H2>The Volunteer Who Wants To Make CGI Easy</H2>

          By <A HREF = "mailto:shoba@i-2000.com">Shoba Narayan</A>
</CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
               In the fall of 1995, Eric Tachibana put up his
          first CGI application on the Web. A modest bulletin
          board script, the end result hardly reflected the long
          hours he spent piecing it together from the mostly
          incomprehensible CGI applications he found online and in
          books.
<P>
               Tachibana acknowledged that the project was too
          complex for a beginner trying to learn CGI scripting.
          But like so many other Web developers-in-training, he
          was given an assignment with a fast-approaching
          deadline--the project was for his job at the Electronic
          Frontier Foundation--and it needed to be completed,
          regardless of how well prepared he was to do so.
<P>
               "Last August, one morning at 4 a.m., red-eyed and
          dizzy, I vowed that if I ever got a script to run, I
          would make the script freely available to others so that
          they wouldn't have to struggle like I did," Tachibana
          said.
<P>
               Thus began Selena Sol's Public Domain Script
          Archive. (Selena Sol is Tachibana's pseudonym and was
          invented by inverting the letters in the name Los
          Angeles, minus the letter G). Over the next nine months,
          Tachibana slowly filled his Web site with CGI scripts
          and added a FAQ, an offsite resource section and a
          help-found area. Immediately, he said, "The site was a
          fantastic success." Thousands of Netizens cruised the
          site, downloaded his scripts and successfully put them
          in place on servers all over the world.
<P>
   <B>       Learning By Example</B>
<P>
          At the time he started his online script archive,
          Tachibana said, there were very few books on advanced
          CGI techniques. Broader HTML tomes tended to include
          only a few "fluffy" CGI chapters. While freeware and
          shareware scripts were widely available on the Web, most
          were difficult to understand; they seemed written for
          experts rather than novices.
<P>
               There were also few collected resources for finding
          such crucial CGI information. Tachibana's first bulletin
          board script, for example, used a form processing
          routine he found in Robert Mudry's book "Serving the
          Web," some array handling routines from Randall
          Schwartz's "Learning Perl," some HTML management
          functions from a Web site called Matt Wright's Script
          Archive, and various routines from a number of other
          sites.
<P>
               "I spent many, many hours with "Learning Perl' in
          one hand and a printout of some CGI application in the
          other, trying desperately to decrypt the routines," says
          Tachibana.
<P>
               "I also decided to document each design decision I
          made and every type of Perl trick I used, so that people
          who visited my Web site would have a pretty good idea of
          how things worked."
<P>
               The most requested scripts, he said, include
          Database Manager and Search (as a duo), Chat, HTML/
          Database Web Store, BBS, Calendar, Authentication, Form
          Processor, Guestbook, Keyword Search, Multiple Choice
          Grader, Mailing List Manager, Classified Ad Manager,
          Fortune Cookie, and Random Banner Generator. All these
          are ones that Tachibana wrote himself.
<P>
               Other popular scripts that he didn't write but has
          added to the archive include Site Counter; Browser
          Matcher, which identifies visitors to a site; HTML Web
          Editor, which helps edit an HTML page on a site via CGI
          scripting; and Redirection, which sends a client to
          another page automatically.
<P>
<B>          Sharing The Wealth</B>
<P>
          Even as development resources for Java-based
          interactivity are increasing, Tachibana still sees a
          great need for providing CGI support and sharing those
          resources.
<P>
               "CGI and Java do different things," Tachibana said.
          "Java is excellent for animation, CGI is better for
          databasing. Java is run on the client's computer, and
          CGI is better suited for things that need to be run on
          the server end. Java is for companies, and CGI is for
          the common man." Other technological trends that
          Tachibana is following closely are secured transaction,
          user-interface technologies, the network computer and
          bandwidth.
<P>
               While Tachibana doesn't work full-time for the EFF
          anymore, he still volunteers about 20 hours a week for
          the group and holds his old title of online services
          coordinator. He gets about 30 to 40 requests for
          freelancing work per day, but is only able to take one
          per week, if that. His main mission is to disseminate
          information on the Web.
<P>
               "I don't believe in intellectual property. By
          giving away information, I am not losing money, I am
          gaining opportunities," Tachibana said, "I want to
          create a human-technology synthesis rather than a Net
          based on capitalism and commercialism. My ancestors
          fought in wars to make humanity a better place. If all I
          have to do is create and give away software, I'm getting
          off easy."
<P>
               Tachibana has just finished an 800-page book called
          "Instant Web Scripts with CGI," to be published by
          MIS:Press. The book is for people "who don't care how
          CGI works, they just want to get it to work," he says.
          However, Tachibana doesn't see himself as a book writer.
          "It was such an immense chore," he said. "I like
          teaching, but I prefer exploring. I prefer being a
          student to a teacher."
<P>
               Now that he has the book out of the way, Tachibana
          is trying his best to get hired by Netscape as a
          consultant. He hopes to help a multinational based in
          Asia create intranets so that he can incorporate CGI,
          database integration, Java and Web design into his job.
          He says that he would really like to work in Netscape
          Asia, since he believes that all the future advances of
          the information age will come from southeast
          Asia--Malaysia, Japan, China and Hong Kong.
<P>
               "I think the Eastern mindset is more representative
          of the ideology that would work in an information age.
          They are less individual-focused, more process-oriented;
          they think circularly rather than linearly; they have a
          better ability to handle chaos."
<P>
               If he moves to Asia, what will become of the CGI
          script archive? Tachibana wants to try to get his CGI
          script archive to a "very self-regulating" state where
          it will answer people's questions by itself. He wants to
          work on the interface and the FAQ and refine the scripts
          so that people can just download and run them.
<P>
               Tachibana rules out Java as an addition to his Web
          site, "since Gamelan has done such a complete job with
          Java." However, he admits that making his Web site
          self-sufficient may not be possible. "The whole point of
          the Web is that it is always a process and not a
          product. I think I will be involved in the Web site for
          longer than I will want to be," he said ruefully.
<P>
          --------------------------------------------------------
<P>
          Reprinted from Web Week, Volume 2, Issue 11, August 5,
<BR>          1996 © Mecklermedia Corp. All rights reserved. Keywords:
<BR>          design, HTMLtools Date: 19960805
<P>
