<TITLE> Applying Library Principles to Computers</TITLE>
<H1><IMG SRC="/CAF/cafnews.gif"> 
Applying Library Intellectual Freedom Principles to Public and
Academic Computers
</h1><p>
by Carl M. Kadie (kadie@eff.org)<p>
For <i> Computers, Freedom, and Privacy '94 on March 26, 1994</i><p>
Version 2 (pretty much as presented at the conference, corrections requested)<p>

<A Name="Contents"><h2>Contents</h2></a>
<ul>
<li><A href="#Resources">Resources</a>
<li><A href="#Introduction">Introduction</a>
<li><A href="#TopPolicies">Top Library Intellectual Freedom Policies</a>
<li><A href="#Overview">Overview</a>
<li><A href="#NYX">The Case of NYX</a>
<li><A href="#CICA">The Case of CICA</a>
<li><A href="#greek">The Case of the Greek List</a>
<li><A href="#Free-Net">The Case of the Free-Net</a>
<li><A href="#iastate">The Case of Iowa State University</a>
<li><A href="#vchip">The Case of the V-Chip</a>
<li><A href="#cert">The Case of CERT</a>
<li><A href="#k12">The Case of K-12</a>
<li><A href="#Conclusion">Conclusion</a>
</ul>

<A Name="Resources"><h2>Resources</h2></a>

