<h1><img src="/Icons/pgp_icon.gif" ALT="">
<a name="top">EFF &quot;Net Tools - Privacy &amp; Security - Pretty Good Privacy (PGP)&quot; Archive</a></h1>

<H5>http://www.eff.org/pub/Net_info/Tools/Crypto/PGP/
</H5>



<h6>Last Updated Sun Jan 05 19:14:35 PDT 1997</h6><br>
<TABLE BORDER=4 CELLPADDING=4 CELLSPACING=4>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
<TD><A HREF="#files">Files</A></TD><h6></h6>
<TD><A HREF="#dirs">Subdirectories</A></TD><h6></h6>
<TD><A HREF="#onsite">On-Site Links</A></TD><h6></h6>
<TD><A HREF="#offsite">Off-Site Links</A></TD>
</TR></TABLE>


<P></CENTER><BR><HR>
<BR><h2><A NAME="files">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/doc1_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40 ALT=""></A>
Files in this Archive</h2>

<DL>
<DT><a href="README"><B>README</B></a>
<DD>Info on where and how to get PGP itself.
<DT><a href="README.auto-pgp"><B>README.auto-pgp</B></a>
<DD>information about the auto-pgp software, below.
<DT><a href="auto-pgp.tar.gz"><B>auto-pgp.tar.gz</B></a>
<DD>Emacs Auto-PGP 1.03 - This is a bunch of Elisp, Perl and C
    to allow you to integrate PGP2 (version 2.6[ui] or later)
    into your Emacs mailreader (and perhaps also your
    newsreader). [See README.auto-pgp for a list of features,
    and other info.]
<DT><a href="auto-pgp.tar.gz.sig"><B>auto-pgp.tar.gz.sig</B></a>
<DD>PGP signature for verifying auto-pgp.tar.gz
<DT><a href="elm_pgp_filter.pl"><B>elm_pgp_filter.pl</B></a>
<DD>PERL script for use with elm mailer - filters for
    presence of digital signatures in messages.
<DT><a href="fake_pgp.pl"><B>fake_pgp.pl</B></a>
<DD>PERL script for generating PGP look-alike message.
    Completely fake, does not actually encrypt anything,
    and will not fool PGP. Why use this? Beats me.
<DT><a href="geopgp1.pl"><B>geopgp1.pl</B></a>
<DD>This is a PERL script that takes as input a PGP encrypted,
    ascii output file. It skips the headers and stuff, and
    converts every character in the body into a geographic name. 
    The author says: &quot;So maybe this can be used to mail other
    people lists of geographic names rather than encrypted
    messages since I've heard some networks frown upon encrypted
    mail :-)&quot;
<DT><a href="getpgp.faq"><B>getpgp.faq</B></a>
<DD>Michael Johnson's June 1994 FAQ-style document
    regarding where and how to get various versions of PGP
<DT><a href="keys0624.pgp.gz"><B>keys0624.pgp.gz</B></a>
<DD>The Internet world-wide PGP public key ring - thousands
    of keys. This is a gzip-compressed PGP keyring. WARNING:
    unless you wish to sit for many hours waiting for this
    keyfile to process, rename your keyring to pubtemp.pgp,
    rename this pubring.pgp, and add the contents of pubtemp.pgp
    to the new pubring.pgp, rather than adding this keyring to
    yours. Alternately, just keep it as a separate key ring,
    and use it when you need to.
<DT><a href="keyservers.faq"><B>keyservers.faq</B></a>
<DD>list of PGP public key servers which allow one to
    exchange public keys running through the internet and UUCP
    mail systems. will be out of date after PGP 2.6
<DT><a href="leahy_pgp_960502_net.letter"><B>leahy_pgp_960502_net.letter</B></a>
<DD>Sen. Leahy's open letter to the Net community,
    on PGP, encryption and new privacy legislation. This appears to be the
    first time any US Senator has publicly used the PGP encryption program.
<DT><a href="legal_viacrypt.pgp"><B>legal_viacrypt.pgp</B></a>
<DD>information on Viacrypt's version of PGP 2.6 which
    uses RSA instead of RSAREF code and thus, is not
    subject to RSAREF license.
<DT><a href="macpgp.faq"><B>macpgp.faq</B></a>
<DD>Xenon's November 1993 FAQ regarding macPGP
<DT><a href="macpgpkit171.sea.hqx"><B>macpgpkit171.sea.hqx</B></a>
<DD>MacPGP Kit 1.7.1: A collection of scripts and tools
    for MacPGP (drag-n-drop en/decryption with specific parameters, 
    decryption from Eudora, etc.) Very fancy. It's big, but you can 
    discard the parts you don't need.
<DT><a href="mlsc100.exe"><B>mlsc100.exe</B></a>
<DD>Mollusc 1.00, a (new, as of July 1996) Windows PGP front-end.
    Claims to integrate seamlessly with your email (PMail, Eudora, WinCIM,
    Ameol, etc.), to reduce PGP operations to &quot;just one click&quot;, to have
    good key management options, comprehensive help system, etc. (Don't
    worry, a large proportion of this file's 600K+ file size is the
    included VRBRUN300.DLL file required by Molusc and many other Windows
    programs. Chances are you already have it. The application itself if
    pretty small, and not a memory hog.) This is a self-extracting ZIP
    archive. Just run it, and it will expand itself. 
<DT><a href="pgp-dot-net.announce"><B>pgp-dot-net.announce</B></a>
<DD>announcement of the new Internet domain pgp.net, and
    the world-wide automated PGP keyservice it provides (ftp service to
    PGP-related archives will be next.)
<DT><a href="pgp.faq"><B>pgp.faq</B></a>
<DD>PGP Frequently Asked Questions &amp; Answers; comprised of 4
    sections: General FAQ, Appendix (Glossary), info on the politics
    of PGP, and Congress/White House contact info.
<DT><a href="pgp26doc.zip"><B>pgp26doc.zip</B></a>
<DD>documentation (only! no source or other export-restricted 
    materials) for PGP 2.6 (US/Canadian version)
<DT><a href="pgp2_6.faq"><B>pgp2_6.faq</B></a>
<DD>Abelson, Schiller, LaMacchia, &amp; Atkin's June 1994 FAQ for PGP 2.6
<DT><a href="pgp_nutshell.guide"><B>pgp_nutshell.guide</B></a>
<DD>&quot;PGP in a Nutshell&quot; - short guide for PGP beginners
    (ASCII text version)
<DT><a href="pgp_nutshell.amigaguide.gz"><B>pgp_nutshell.amigaguide.gz</B></a>
<DD>&quot;PGP in a Nutshell&quot; - gzip-compressed AmigaGuide
    version (do &quot;get pgp_nutshell.amigaguide&quot; without
    .gz to have it auto-decompressed for you.)
<DT><a href="pgp_via_email.note"><B>pgp_via_email.note</B></a>
<DD>David Clunie's March 1993 note on how to get sources
    for PGP.
<DT><a href="pgs099ee.zip"><B>pgs099ee.zip</B></a>
<DD>Pretty Good Shell, a DOS PGP shell program (menuing, but non-
    graphical. Fast.) Contains no crypto code. This is just 
    a shell, and requires PGP. Public beta version. Worked 
    fine when tested here.
<DT><a href="pgpshe32.zip"><B>pgpshe32.zip</B></a>
<DD>PGPShell, a DOS GUI-like shell/menu interface for the PGP
    encryption program. Very nice program, though slow to
    handle large keyrings. Contains no crypto code. This is
    just a shell, and requires PGP.
<DT><a href="pgpsites.list"><B>pgpsites.list</B></a>
<DD>Jeff Davis' April 1994 list of where to find PGP on the net
<DT><a href="pgpw26.zip"><B>pgpw26.zip</B></a>
<DD>PGPWin 2.6, a Windows shell for PGP making the encryption
    program more intuitive for GUI usage. [Does not contain crypto
    code, and requires PGP. It's just a shell.]
<DT><a href="pgpwf31.zip"><B>pgpwf31.zip</B></a>
<DD>This is a Windows front end for PGP, PGPWinFront. It's freeware
    and makes using PGP very easy. Please ensure the integrity of
    the file with the enclosed digital signature. [Does not
    contain crypto code, and requires PGP. It's just a shell.]
<DT><a href="stealth.tar.gz"><B>stealth.tar.gz</B></a>
<DD>Stealth, the steganography program for PGP. Hide
    PGP-encrypted messages inside JPEGs and other graphic files,
    almost impossible to detect! This is the Unix (source)
    version. [Does not contain crypto code, and requires PGP. 
    It's just a shell.]
<DT><a href="stealth.zip"><B>stealth.zip</B></a>
<DD>Stealth, the steganography program for PGP. Hide
    PGP-encrypted messages inside JPEGs and other graphic files,
    almost impossible to detect! This is the DOS (source)
    version - does NOT include binaries. [Does not contain crypto
    code, and requires PGP. It's just a shell.]
<DT><a href="winpgp.zip"><B>winpgp.zip</B></a>
<DD>similar to pgpw26.zip, but has no key management features.
    [Does not contain crypto code, and requires PGP. It's just
    a shell.] 
<DT><a href="zimmermann-pgp2_6.statement"><B>zimmermann-pgp2_6.statement</B></a>
<DD>Phillip Zimmermann's May 1994 statement
    briefly describing PGP 2.6
</DL>

